Nassim Nicholas Taleb literally just posted this on his YouTube channel. It's short but there's a point where he talks about maximum drawdowns and how it's useful in assessing risk. I think it blends perfectly with cryptocurrency and trading where in this case, Bitcoin had more risk because it had larger drawdowns relative to Etherium. So in retrospect, Etherium was, in one sense, more likely to perform better than Bitcoin.
Final assessment: ETH outperformed BTC during this period.

Based on historical volatility, if we were only 2 days from resolution at current prices, my simulation would suggest 40% BTC, 0.5% ADA, 58% ETH, and 1.5% XRP. Given that we have almost a month of runway though, my simulation suggests 32% BTC, 11% ADA, 40% ETH, and 17% XRP. Seeing that some of the other forecasts, and the sudden shift since I started forecasting, I'm curious to know: have any of you used or built on my simulation? I put it out there for others to use if they want, but I'm curious if you have feedback. For those making forecasts out of step with my simulation, would you be willing to make suggestions about why the forecast should be different? With the approval for crypto currency to be traded via exchange-traded funds (ETF), I think the advantage for Bitcoin to outperform others gets a boost. I tired to see if other crypto currencies were also approved. Basically...if all cryptos were approved...then they should all benefit equally from the increase in demand and capital available to invest. It took me a minute, but I think I found ETF that contain non-Bitcoin. However, since that had to be searched out instead of being in the headlines about the new ETF, it will push Bitcoin slightly ahead and while rates of gain might equal out again, then a momentary advantage is still an advantage.

BTC and ETH catalysts (BTH ETF, BTC legal, ETH Altair upgrade–closer to proof-of-stake, ETH connection to Facebook Meta, and portfolio managers need to close the year with strong performing cryptos in their portfolio). In the absence of catalysts for ADA and XRP, BTC and ETH will retain their lead over the other two. Although BTC gain is greater than BTC currently, I see ETH being a stronger performer due to Metadata hype and the technological change towards proof-of-stake in their platform. I don’t want to throw ADA out of the running since it can store metadata as well.
Cardano is stable to slightly decreasing and doesn't appear likely to change much. Same with Ripple. Bitcoin confidence seems high and growing as does Ethereum.

Updating to balance more in the direction of some of the forecasters I follow while still leaning heavily on the Monte Carlo simulation results to inform my "outside view". See this comment for details on the simulation: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1349335

My ideal would be to use MCMC, but to get this out quickly, I put together a quick version of a Monte Carlo simulation that forces the cryptocurrencies to move according to how they are directionally correlated with respect to Bitcoin (e.g. in the real world, ETH moves the same direction as BTC about 80% of the time, so they must also share the same directionality 80% of the time in the simulation). The results surprised me. My interpretation for the relative success of XRP compared to what I would have expected is that, in the event that the crypto market takes a dive, XRP is the least correlated with the others (although it is still highly correlated) and will likely fare the best. I suspect the crowd is underestimating the volatility of the cryptocurrency market. This is a shot in the dark for me as I lack knowledge on crypto investing and think it to be more of an emotional buy than stocks are. Yes we can look back at the performance of a crypto just as we can with a stock for a company; however, crypto is not attached to a traded company nor is it aligned with a physical form of currency. This makes crypto tougher to speculate than an emerging tech company that is getting ready for IPO. I'm basing my prediction based on market caps. Bitcoin has the largest market cap, followed by Etherium, then Cardano, and finally Ripple. All that being said, I feel that one strong reddit group with a timely post could change the tide on performance for any of these currencies.

Forbes reported the Top 10 Cryptocurrencies in October 2021 as: 1. BITCOIN(BTC), 2. Etherium (ETH), 3. Tether (USDT), 4. Cardano (ADA), 5. Binance Coin (BNB), 6. XRP (XRP), 7. Solana (SOL), 8. USD Coin (USDC), 9. Polkadot (DOT), and 10. Dogecoin (DOGE) (2021). US News reported, The Seven Contenders for the Best Crypto to Buy for 2021 as: 1. Bitcoin, 2. Bitcoin Cash, 3. Ethereum, 4. Cardano, 5. Dogecoin, 6. Binance Coin, and 7. Polkadot (2021). The CoinDesk Quarterly Review (Third Quarter 2021) assessed, “Q3 2021 was a welcome relief for the market after BTC and ETH hit all-time highs in early Q2 2021, only to come tumbling down. Both assets performed well from a price perspective, adding 25.0% and 31.8%, respectively. It felt as though the market was taking a breather, which revealed itself through lower volatility measures than in any other quarter this year, albeit with levels still far above established macro assets. On top of that, BTC proved mostly uncorrelated with gold, the S&P 500, bonds, and the US dollar, highlighting BTC could have a unique place in portfolios” (pg.2). The report also stated, “BTC and ETH outperformed traditional benchmarks, and ETH continued its winning streak against BTC, having outperformed the preeminent cryptocurrency by market capitalization in each 2021 quarter, hinting at the possibility that more money, institutional and retail, maybe entering the fold” (pg.4). Based on reporting and ratings, Etherium will perform best between 27 May 2021 and November 2021 (53%) (moderate-confidence), followed by BITCOIN (47%) (moderate-confidence).

My prediction is based on a few factors the largest being past data Bitcoin remains the most stable form of Cryptocurrency on the market and still controls the lions share of it even as competitors have arisen. Meaning large market upheaval or unexpected events are unlikely to affect it as much. Furthermore, bit coin is the easiest to access via kiosks even the store I work at has a kiosk specifically for Bitcoin. While other crypto currency has kiosks most are meant short short term investment and quick profits. Finally, with the new U.S Department of justice task force focused on crypto currency cyber crime it could make the smaller currencies have issues as they are used often in illegal activities. While Bitcoin is also used in these illegal transactions due to its stability it’s less likely to be effected by this. The overall issue with crypto currency is outside of Bitcoin it is very volatile so any of them could be the most profitable.

Reasoning: Bitcoin has shown to have longevity in the market, and is the most dominant cryptocurrency. Ethereum is another great option, as it is the second largest cryptocurrency behind bitcoin. Although Ethereum has an overall increase of 655.74% according to National World, they are still recovering from a market crash earlier this year. Cardano on the other hand has shown exponential growth on the crypto market, but is fairly new so it is hard to judge it's market durability at this point. Overall though it has had a market increase of 1,714,52% increase over last year according to National World. According to Forbes this number is even higher since it was started in 2017, at around 10,500%. XRP seems to be a bit out of the race at this point following China's crackdown on crypto, which caused the price to cut in thirds despite a strong year for the currency.

Bitcoin is the most established cryptocurrency and has a better price cap and volume compared with other CCs. Bitcoin is also legal tender in El Salvador and may be used in different countries and stores/online sales sites soon. However, because Bitcoin's prices are so high, currently $49,245, investors may place their money in CCs they can get a better return on for their money, and ETH and Cardano fall in this category. ETH is more established and trusted, giving it an advantage over Cardano. XRP appears to have much higher volatility (prices range from ~$.17 to $1.94 over the past year). There is a discussion that XRP may be the CC of choice because ETH and Cardano are down ~15%, but it is total speculation. If prices go up, it is only because the masses jump on media predictions and meme recommendations.

Bitcoin has shown consistently strong returns, confidence and positive responses. Etherium has also shown strong returns and consumer confidence. Ripple and Cardano are less well know with much more variable performance and less consistent positive consumer sentiment.

China saying it won't allow crypto currencies - that eliminates businesses and investors. However, it removes a question mark from a significant government/investors who can influence the market, which increases stability (after previous partial bans). Bitcoin options had an expiration of 01 Oct, that helped the value recover from losses earlier in September. Based on the closeout date of this question, that gives Bitcoin a higher starting value leading off the final 60 days of the window. Additionally, name recognition gives Bitcoin a significant advantage to remain the highest value when the window closes. This is also a risk because if there is a drop, Bitcoin will suffer much more value loss than the other lesser known options. However, with instability in the markets due to inflation concerns, Evergrande bankruptcy/bailout consequences, I do no suspect crypto "market shares" will be shaken up within these "competitors.

Judging from the CoinDesk projections of returns on investments, the performance of Cardano overall has been consistently better with a 1year return of 2306.86% far exceeding the other three cryptocurrencies. As well, looking at the daily performance charts, Cardano has been the least volatile over the period from 27 May 2021 to present. In addition, looking at the monthly average differential for each of the four cryptocurrencies, Cardano performs better overall increasing value by about 6.7% each month on average. Bitcoin, though at higher overall value, has only increased its value by about 2.5% each month on average with Etherium at negative rates and XRP just about breaking even. Given that the end of the forecast period is less than two months away, these trends are likely to generally continue.

According to CoinDesk, the second quarter of 2021 was characterized by price retracing in most crypto assets. The only assets that were in the green for 2021 Q2 were XRP, ADA and ETH, the native cryptocurrencies of the XRP Ledger, Cardano and Ethereum blockchains, which have continued their upward march returning 22%, 19% and 16%, respectively as reported by CoinDesk. Despite ending the quarter at a loss, BTC and ETH hit new all-time price highs earlier in the season. For bitcoin, 20% drops are common on the way to new all-time highs according to CoinDesk. However, Some analysts characterize the recent upside move in cryptocurrencies as an oversold bounce. Technically, that occurs when prices become stretched to the downside, which encourages short sellers to exit their positions. Still, several risks remain that could limit further upside. One area of concern is the effort by U.S. and European authorities to enact stricter measures for users to exchange crypto for fiat currencies. This will be an ongoing development. Based on the charts, I calculated that as of October 1, 2021 Cardano was the best performer with a 6 month return of 86.39%, followed by XRP at 77.76%. For the long term, Bitcoin and Ethereum have the most name recognition and the least speculative. My top 3 in this forecast are Bitcoin, Ethereum and Cardano, with Cardano outpacing in the short haul. @SEC.gov reports that Ripple is involved in litigation concerning an SEC complaint, filed in federal district court in Manhattan that charges Ripple defendants with violating the registration provisions of the Securities Act of 1933, and seeks injunctive relief, disgorgement with prejudgment interest, and civil penalties. This litigation if successful could have long term effects on Ripple's viability.

"Perform best" is a very loaded term in the current crypto environment. As alternative currencies still vie for acceptability, Bitcoin remains in the "lead," but it's still not clear at this point whether this is a race to the top or one to the bottom. Add lots of noise/technical/meme trading, and it is a virtual certainty that the "prices" of all of these crypto currencies on 11/29 (whatever they may be) will me more or less meaningless. Oh well, here goes nothing!

One key factor to keep in mind is that when Bitcoin moves, "alt-coins" generally move in the same direction but with higher % magnitude. As a result, if Bitcoin makes another leg down, ETH, ADA, and XRP are likely to move down harder. The same applies to the opposite direction.
